The selective sensing of amoxicillin is indicated by the oxidation peak current, which is due to the electro-oxidation process occurred at the p-hydroxy substituent of amoxicillin (Scheme 3
                        ). Interference from other antibiotics on the electrochemical performance of amoxicillin was further analyzed. The voltammetric response of 0.001 µM amoxicillin in the presence of other potential interferents like levofloxacin (LEV), ciprofloxacin (CIP), tetracycline (TETRA), cloxacillin (CLOXA), kanamycin (KANA), vancomycin (VANCO), and doxycycline (DOX) are depicted in Fig. 9
                        a, even though the concentration of these ions may much higher than the amoxicillin concentration, there was no apparent interference in amoxicillin sensing. The prolonged stability of the modified electrode was analyzed using CV in PBS solution and depicted in Fig. 9b. As demonstrated, the CV responses of the modified electrode exhibited nearly constant over a period of 30 days with an RSD of 1.45 %. This finding indicated that the proposed sensor has long-lasting stability.

Due to their great water solubility, fluorescence, and stability, the fabricated carbon dots were effectively used as fluorescent ink for writing and drawing [39]. Fig. 11
                         illustrates photographic images of the aqueous dispersion of NCDs illuminated with a UV lamp. These images reveal the important usage of NCDs as ink with exceptional photostability. This fluorescent ink is a potential substitute for traditional fluorescent ink because it is cheap, pollution free, biocompatible, and easy to use [40,41] (Table 1
                        ).
